6017"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I01627","children_ids":["HD6030"],"marriage_number":1}],"tags":["artist","author","extraordinary_longevity","painter"],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"arts","header":"Artist and chronicler of a pioneer school","body":"Emily Noyes Vanderpoel was a painter and writer whose 1903 'Chronicles of a Pioneer School' preserved the history of Litchfield's Female Academy. She also published an influential study of color in design.","number":1},{"category":"arts","header":"Her Color Problems anticipated modern abstraction","body":"Vanderpoel's 1902 'Color Problems' translated color theory into hundred-square grids sampling everything from mummy cases to butterfly wings. Long overlooked, the book is now read as anticipating Klee, Albers, and Rothko by decades.","number":2},{"category":"social_reform","header":"She remade Litchfield in Colonial Revival","body":"As curator of the Litchfield Historical Society, Vanderpoel drove the town's Colonial Revival, behind the restorations of the Congregational Church and the Litchfield Law School. She also helped found the local DAR chapter named for her great-grandmother Mary Floyd Tallmadge.","number":3},{"category":"legacy","header":"She finished her son's gift to Litchfield","body":"When her son John Arent died with his library building unfinished, Emily completed the project and set a memorial tablet to him beneath its Palladian window. The building honored her mother, Julia Tallmadge Noyes.","number":4}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[{"artwork_id":"ART082","role":"creator"}],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"X03136","display_label":"her father-in-law, Congressman Aaron Vanderpoel"},{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD3004","display_label":"led Hartford's preservation as Vanderpoel did Litchfield's"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Emily Caroline","l